segments.text: In your efforts to build the department, did you or any of your colleagues go to any meetings to recruit students?
Let me see.
Let me tell you how I handled it.
You know, at one time, A&M says, you're going to teach this class at 8 o'clock and 10 o'clock and so forth.
And they told me, what are you going to teach and when are you going to teach?
Well, I knew that was wrong philosophy.
So I said, I want you to give me your
Three requests of what you want to teach and what time you want to teach it, and I'll work it out for you.
I've got me a great big week map and filled in all of these.
And it developed.
There were people who liked 8 o'clock, people who liked 10 o'clock.
You didn't have to say, you're going to do this.
When they gave me that back, I could fill in the blanks.
And I got there, everybody told me what they wanted.
Got what they wanted at the time, and no hassle.
And I'm having trouble in life.
If you treat people that way, you don't
But I wasn't about to sit there and say, look, you're going to teach them this this time, this this time.
Well, a lot of people don't like 8 o'clock.
They like 10 o'clock.
And a lot of people who don't like 10 o'clock will take 8 o'clock.
It works out.
You just have to treat people the way you would like to be treated and be fair to everybody.
And that was the philosophy I used.
And I remember when we went over a 50% girl, so they really went into action.
How many years did that take?
Do you remember?
Seven.
Seven.
So from 68 to... From 70.
No.
I didn't have anything to do with the teaching.
They only let me have a key until 69.
I got a key.
In January of 70, they gave me all of it.
Okay.
And I had to rebuild from that 70.
That's right, 70.
And in seven years, we had the 540 kids, a new building, and the $2 million endowed chair from Ben's family.
And that's about as fast as you can build.
But anyway, I enjoyed that.
As I said, the greatest experience of my life was rebuilding Horticulture to a viable building, a viable department.
And I had to write the history of the department because I had known
or what it was as students.
And I knew we had good professors back there.
Mr. Bryson was a top professor.
Dr. Adrian was a top professor.
And I had both of them.
You take the good and leave the rest as you go along.
And of course, with what they had and your philosophy all mixed together, you come up with a viable mix.
And that was what we did in horticulture.
When you first became responsible for the department, describe the facilities and the office space that the department had when you started.
OK, we had a small office for myself and a small office next door.
And we had two other offices.
And we had some offices that were occupied

forestry and where were those they were they had they were in in rooms that we needed but what building uh old horticulture building uh plant science building no plant science building because for me we just had a meager space we had one hall one off and down the hall for um floriculture and then we had the two
There's three offices in the rest of the suite.
But Forestry had some sites that they had a day and just assumed those rooms.
And they were really in our room, but we couldn't get them back.
Luckily, I was on the Master Plan Committee, and Perry Atkinson was on that.
And he supported me.
What we needed was a horticulture building, something where we could grow.
But we had no space to grow whatever.
And he supported me.
And together, he got an extra $5 million grant through Dr. Kunkel to build a horticulture.
When Perry Atkinson told Kunkel that we desperately needed space, that opened the door.
And we did get the building.
But I knew we had $13 million for the building.
And our parents told us, that's not enough.
So he was on the big committee.
And together, we got an extra $5 million.
And we got that $18 million.
And I never will forget that one of the people, well, I'll tell you.
Let me think of his name.
He just died recently.
He was the rose man from Tyler.
And DeWorth brought him down and then wanted to fire him.
And Bloodworth wouldn't let him fire him.
So I inherited him.
And he said it was like a breath of fresh air coming in.
Because I wouldn't take anything off of DeWorth.
See, DeWorth had destroyed landscape architecture completely in the years.
Well, Mr. Hensel had hired Bob White, and he was building landscape architecture.
But after Mr. Hensel died, DeWorth would give Bob White no help, no support, whatever.
And finally, he moved to Houston and opened a practice.
Then DeWorth, well, I came along.
And I wouldn't take a leap off of DeWorth, because I knew not to.
But we finally got Bob White back.
But you see, Bob White then went from the College of Agriculture to the College of Engineering, where landscape architecture belonged.
And then it became, thus, the College of Environmental Design.
And he was there and went to Harvard there.
And Robert White has done a masterful job.
I call him the Renaissance man in landscape architecture.
And he was really a good man, but DeWorth just sacrificed him for what he did.
But anyway, DeWorth could get along with nobody and didn't even try to because he had tenure.
But they finally retired him.
All right, so you served for how many years as department head?
No, I didn't serve department head.
I've served...
I mean, as the head of that part of the... From 70 till... 70 to 71.
Wait a minute.
Seven years.
Seven years.
We rebuilt that thing completely.
And all we did in the world was open the door, tell the students you're welcome.
I said, don't ever see me with the door locked.
I wouldn't let them lock the door.
She would knock on the door to get in.
I said, never again.
And my thinking, and I told them, I said, when you don't have any students to teach, you don't have a job here.
And just get that through your head right now.
And we've got work to do.
I felt like you had to be firm, fair, and consistent all the way through this.
And that's what I tried to do all the time.
But I was so delighted that at the end of seven years, we had a viable department.
And then they said, well, we have to have a PhD to hit it.
And that's when they got Mr. Grolick.
Now, who were the key people that supported that growth, that helped you with it outside the department?
You mentioned... Oh, Bloodworth.
Okay.
And Dick Potts.
Dick Potts was our friend.
He was the associate, as associate dean.
Associate dean.
Wonderful person.
Just, I don't think I could have ever done harder culture without his help.
I'd go down and he'd support me on, see, I had to have, I had all the advising and counseling for every member of the department.
Nobody ever told those kids what to take or when to take them or anything else.
There was some kids that stayed in school a year or two long
They lost a lot of money that way, kids.
But I'd make up a course of study, and I'd tell them how to do it and when to do it.
And they had to do this.
The students can't read the catalog and know how to do this.
If you don't give them some help, they're lost.
So I would guide them as best I could.
I had all of them myself.
Nobody else did it.
But Dick Potts would help me.
When I got in a real bind with a kid to get him out of school, I'd do this.
I'll give you an example of one student.
It wasn't an A&M, it was a Texas Tech choir taught three years.
We had a young man who was 90% disabled from mental, shell-shocked, and nobody worked with him.
So I thought, well, I'm going to take him on and make a human out of him.
So I knew it was just like a timber box.
The least thing could set him off.
So he needed help.
three or four green points to graduate.
And he had taken a course over.
So finally I said, now Earl, I want you to take a course over and I'll watch it for you.
But before I could tell him what to take, he enrolled in chemistry.
And he failed chemistry again.
Now we were back to square one.
Well, he was really upset because he failed chemistry.
And I said, now Earl,
You stay with me, and I'm going to guide you through.
We're going to get you out of this university.
And I knew I could get him out of the university if I handled him right.
But you can't just desert a guy like that and never get anywhere with him.
So I worked with him real fine, and I had him almost over the barrier.
And Hilo Urbanski, the head of the org, came in, and he wanted a piece of paper.
And he opened a drawer, and there was Earl's 30th and 40th piece of cardboard he was working on.
And he said, oh, you're just, hell, I'll just take that paper.
You're wasting your time anyway with that man.
And at that minute, he walked in and heard all this.
He was drunk for three days.
I finally got him in the corner.
I said, Earl, don't you ever go around urbanizing again.
I'm going to work you or get you out of university here.
We got him out.
It was 03 or 04 grade points to spare.
And you know that he went off to somewhere else and got a Ph.D. in guidance and counseling?
And that's what brought up, I can think, what would have happened to that kid if I left him alone?
Now, the dean at this time was Harry Kunkel.
No, this was at Texas Tech.
Oh, I'm sorry.
I'm sorry.
All right.
Kunkel was the dean when you were building this department.
And he was supportive of the growth and development.
No, he said, what are you going to do with all these girls?
He said, they can't all be biochemists.
And I said, no, they don't want to be biochemists.
There's a whole other world out there, Dean, besides biochemistry.
And we're going to explore it for you.
I said, don't you realize that the better we look and harder it goes, the better it makes you look better?
And he said, no, no.
He didn't accept that.
Yeah, I had some rough things to overcome with them because they had that old Aggie autocratic way.
And he says, they can't all take a pile.
And I said, they don't want to do it.
All right, and you mentioned Perry Edkisson.
He, at that point, was department?
No, he was assistant dean.
Oh, he was assistant dean.
Describe him.
He was on the math, he was on the, Perry Edkisson was at a high rank on campus.
He was head of entomology, I know, and
I brought a student there one time that discovered in his research, he discovered a new strain of something that had never been done before, original research.
And he said, just send me all the kids like that you can send me.
And from that day on, we were great friends.
And we ended up both on the campus planting.
And that's where we got the money for the horticulture building.
He, Perry Atkinson, is a scholar from way back.
Back to Mr. Rutter a second.
As you worked with him and Mr. Cherry and the others, were you aware of any decline in Mr. Rutter's health?
That was right in my life.
You know, all of a sudden somebody said, Mr. Rutter is sick.
Next thing I knew, he was dead.
And...
LBJ came down, a whole few came down, and I just took over arranging the flowers.
You never saw so many flowers in your barn in days.
And they called me from Florida and said, we got one from the Secretary of State.
We got one from this place in Milwaukee.
Get us a police farm.
And I saved them a police farm.
We stacked them in there that way and did the best we could.
And LBJ came down, and boy, I tell you,
That was one more big day.
I never had any inkling that he was ill. And he died one month before his 60th birthday.
I knew that all of a sudden the campus got quiet.
And it was rumored that he had a heart attack.
And so it was.
The doctor, I'd say the doctor came, and I believe they took him away from there, took him away from there in an ambulance.
The next thing we knew, he'd be gone.
All right.
When Dr. Williams came, what was your first interaction with him?
Great.
Absolutely wonderful.
Never had a world presence.
I said, details.
He was huge.
I did things for him before he ever knew me, before his wife ever got there.
It was just part of the job to get these things done.
And he appreciated it a great deal.
But for a man to come to me and say, I've not met you, I'm Jack Williams, and this man is a short statue.
We need to lower that.
And a minute later, kind of detailed, I never did anything like that.
He didn't write me anything.
He didn't write me a note.
Just note after note after note all the time, thanking me for things that were just a routine part of the job I was supposed to do.
And after his heart trouble, he never was the same, though.
I just, I think, I thought I lost one of the finest friends I'd ever had.
I just thought the world of him.
He'd say, can you get so-and-so to play golf with us this afternoon?
Well, that worked out fine, except every now and then somebody said, I want you to get me and Jake to play golf with the president.
I said, I can't do that.
If he don't want you to play with him, you're not going to do it.
He said, he'll ask me if you want to do it.
And Armin Simpson played with him.
But when he, from the time his heart attack on, he was a completely different man.
And I know you would be, anybody would be.
But I just thought the world and all of him.
And I'm glad we got a building name for him.
Describe, you worked with Mrs. Williams.
Describe her and her personality.
Very different than the thing I was used to.
She wanted to rearrange the way I put the plants around the stage at commencement and things like this.
And she was quite satisfied with the plants and the way we had them arranged and the flowers.
They were quite satisfied with it.
She wanted so she could do them better, which is all right.
I didn't question her.
She loved to do her thing.
We never crossed the line.
That's the way it goes.
All right.
In
As we got near the 100th anniversary, 1976, there were plans to add to the landscaping on the campus.
Did that fall within your?
Yeah, but it fell through.
I didn't buy it.
I had some friends in California that raised roses, red roses.
And I wanted to get a maroon and white rose, Aggie rose.
And that's the right flat of his face.
What happened?
I just proposed it, and nothing ever came of it.
It just died.
Oh, the campus didn't support it?
Nobody supported it.
Oh, really?
Oh.
I gave this to the board at a board meeting.
We were talking about Campus 76 as a theme.
And I couldn't get anybody.
There'll be six campus celebrations.
Now, didn't we plant the trees all the way around the old horse pasture and the golf course?
Wasn't that?
Perimeter trees was out.
But that was not part of that.
That was planned expansion on my part.
Oh, that was not part of the centennial?
No.
I just felt like we needed perimeter trees to mark the campus.
And whereas they were planted on main campus 20 and 30 feet apart where they couldn't grow,
except we didn't mention top.
And that's what's caused a lot of problems up there.
We put them 80 feet from the street and 80 feet apart.
I wanted them back far enough to make a statement in design, and then we wouldn't have to cut them down if we widened anything.
And then they widened, take the avenue, and luckily we didn't ruin the trees.
If, in addition to the maroon and white rows,
Were there any other dreams you had for the centennial that you wish we could have done?
Well, we didn't get the first base of any plans on that.
I don't know whether the rose scared them off or what.
These are very good friends of mine and the number one growers, Tops and Roses in California.
And they grew the Mr. Lincoln.
and Oklahoma that we introduced at the New York's World Fair, both of them.
Illinois built the only brick building on that campus and called it the Land of Lincoln, and they had the figure of him.
They helped get his birthday read.
And so I went over to the lady, and I said, now I have some friends who are hybridizing the rules whose birthday is the next 12th, which is Lincoln's birthday.
and I can get you all the roses you want to play on this place if you'd like to have them."
She said, we'd love to have them.
Well, she and me won for the long fight.
She bought bud faces, and she'd go out every morning and cut three roses.
And in two weeks, two years, she delivered a bud face of Mr. Lincoln to every director of that camp of a fair.
And then we introduced the rose Mr., I mean, Oklahoma there.
When the last day of the fair, people were pulling those things up, roots and all, even grabbing a piece of grass to take with them.
But it was quite an experience.
I was asked if I could do the... Well, first a young man called me one day and said, we would like to get your help on the fair.
Well, I thought they meant the state fair in Oklahoma City.
And he said...
I said, yeah, I can help you.
I said, look, are you talking about the New York World Fair?
I said, I can't speak for that much time, but if Dr. Cross wants me to help you, he says we'll help you.
And so Dr. Cross called me about an hour.
He said, I wish everybody on the staff knew that I was president.
But those people were so great.
And you know, he played football for South Dakota.
And he had a scholarship to wash the dishes.
He said, well, if I figured if I could wash dishes in the girls' dormitory, I'd see every girl in that school.
And sure enough, the prettiest girl in the whole school came through, and I got her.
were beginning to, as the enrollment began to expand under Mr. Rutter and Dr. Williams, the campus had to expand.
Did you have a chance to be a part of the planning?
I was supposed to until Paul Stevens, everything we proposed, Paul Stevens overruled it.
And I wish I could remember the name of the man that had so much trouble with him beside me.
I was supposed to be in on everything, but Stevenson never approved anything that I thought of.
Looking back, if we could undo what we did and do it correctly, what should we have done in planning the master plan at A&M for the growth?
What are some mistakes that... Well, we should have had a master plan, not just a piecemeal.
Everything was done building by building, and it came on the line, and you tried to fit them in or not.
Now, I knew that the main axis was east-west.
Wait a minute, is that right?
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
And we had to terminate that axis somewhere.
It went through the middle of the administration academic building.
And so I terminated it before we got out to that creek or river.
Well, the drainage ditch is back there.
And so we terminated, put the horticulture building as a terminus of that axis.
And then beyond that, we could go other directions.
But we had to terminate that.
axis before it fell off into that creek leading to the river.
And after we got the main axis established, then we could have done cross axes on it.
That kind of planning was the kind that was being done back then.
Now the planning is entirely different.
But you need quadrangles and those kind of things.
What kind of plant life should we have encouraged on the campus?
You mean other than trees?
Well, and trees, both.
Of course, I told you the story of the palms and the oaks.
I still think the lab oaks were all right for the tree of choice.
But I think we should have had a few more in there, different species, if nothing else, just to study.
But there are a lot of real good broadleaf evergreens that we use and are still using.
This thing right here, you saw that tree at lunch?
Is that that one?
That's the name of it.
And it started blooming in November.
Loro Petalum.
L-O-R-O-P-E-T-A-L-U-M. Loro Petalum.
Petalum.
Chinese fringe flower.
Now, that thing has been blooming since November here.
And it'll grow in Colorado State as well.
All right, should we have tried to grow roses?
No.
What kinds of bushes should A&M?
Well, there are a lot of shrubs that we can grow.
One of the best is Pitta's Forum, and it's very good in evergreen, all green.
That's one of the best ones we have.
The school colors are easy to come by.
At the University of Oklahoma, I'd plant
red tulips in front of the boys' dormitories and white tulips in front of the girls' dormitories.
Just, you know, a little bit of fun.
And we're not in a four-season climate.
We're in a four-season climate, we've got a lot of things for.
But you've got to, for instance, nothing is majestic to me as a tall-bearded Irish, but you've got to be in the four-seasons area to get enough coal to make those things majestic.
I used to grow up in Oklahoma all the time,
And as a collection.
And there was Irish shoes with them.
But how did you come out with your raised beds?
So far, so good.
You know, if you have raised beds, you can control the water.
But if you don't have control of your beds, they can let me drown out.
And this is one of the first things I learned about Fred and his home at A&M.
They had just that little place that you could grow those flowers.
And we grew them for it.
Any particular varieties of grass that A&M should have attempted?
Well, before we had irrigation, they would tolerate anything with Bermuda.
And in the shade places, you couldn't grow anything.
So I think a combination of Bermuda grass and St. Augustine will work
with irrigation.
But, you know, if you don't have water, it's bad.
All right.
Under Dr. Williams, did you work with John Calhoun and people like that?
Yes.
I remember John Calhoun came from Oklahoma down there.
He preceded me at A&M.
And I remember
As soon as I got there, we talked to each other.
I remember very well.
He was... Engineering.
Oh yeah, he was engineering.
I didn't have quite as close touch with him as I did with some of the other ag cool things.
In the department, who are the people that deserve the greatest
credit for the growth and development of what became the Department of Horticulture and Floriculture?
Who are the key people that deserve the credit?
Perry Atkinson was as good a key as you can get.
I was the only one that knew the history of the department.
and reworked it into a, we had to have a history of the department.
You see, Dr. Pike was there, and he wanted Dr., or Garlic Man, and we had a lot of people apply for head of that department, real top notch people.
But we only had one candidate, and that was the,
I can't remember his name now, but he was supported and pushed by Dr. Pike, and he just developed that way.
We got this man, and they had been in an acting department for 19 years, and the three of us, Homer Blackhurst, and I can't remember the other name, three of us were professors,
And he asked us to be his sounding board.
And so every time he'd ask us anything, we'd tell him, and he'd do the exact opposite.
And every time, he got his tits from a ringer.
His tail would crack or something else.
And finally, he couldn't even get an appointment with the dean.
Nobody would talk to him.
And he finally just evaporated.
As the department was growing, did you all have a program at some other institution you were using as a model?
No.
I was just using what I knew in common sense.
Now, let me tell you what I...
I had a thought there.
I forgot.
Oh, I had asked those...
And I told you, there were nine academicians there.
And it wasn't an academic problem.
It was a management problem.
And the best thing I had to do working for me was I asked them to give me a first, second, third choice.
